# Chat Bots

Nocturne ships a multi-platform bot that lets people **query glucose** and **receive alerts**
from the messaging apps they already use. Four platforms are supported:

- [Discord](/docs/bots/discord)
- [Slack](/docs/bots/slack)
- [Telegram](/docs/bots/telegram)
- [WhatsApp](/docs/bots/whatsapp)

Email delivery is handled by a separate provider — see [Email Alerts (Resend)](/docs/alerts/email).

All four platforms follow the same shape: create an app on the platform, collect its
credentials, point its webhook at your Nocturne instance, and enter the credentials in
Nocturne. The per-platform pages cover the steps unique to each one; this page covers the
parts they share.

## What the bot can do

Once a platform is connected and a user has linked their account, they can:

| Command | What it does |
|---------|--------------|
| `/bg` _(or `/glucose`)_ | Show the latest glucose reading and trend |
| `/connect` | Link the chat account to a Nocturne account |
| `/disconnect` | Unlink a Nocturne account |
| `/status` | Show linked accounts and their status |

The bot can also **deliver alerts**. Add the platform as a delivery channel on an alert rule
(see **Receiving alerts** below) and excursions are pushed to the linked chat — with
**Acknowledge** and **Resolve** actions built into the message.

## Linking accounts

A chat account has to be linked to a Nocturne account before it can see any glucose data.
PHI is never stored on the chat platform — every reading is fetched over HTTPS through the
Nocturne API at request time, scoped to the linked account.

To link, a user runs `/connect` in the chat app. The bot replies with a one-time
authorization link on your instance; signing in there ties their chat user ID to a Nocturne
account. One chat user can link **several** accounts (e.g. a parent following two children),
each given a short **label** used to disambiguate: `/bg lily`. One link is the **default**
and is used when no label is given.

<Callout type="info" title="BASE_DOMAIN is required">
  The bot builds <code>/connect</code> authorization links from your instance's
  <code>BASE_DOMAIN</code>. This is already set on any working Nocturne deployment; if links
  point at the wrong host, check that value first.
</Callout>

## Configuring credentials

Every platform's credentials can be supplied two ways. Pick whichever fits your deployment.

### Option A: Admin UI

1. Sign in to your Nocturne instance as an admin.
2. Go to **Settings > Admin > Integrations**.
3. Find the platform's card, fill in its fields, turn the **Enabled** switch on, and click **Save**.

Credentials entered here are **encrypted at rest** and stored per-instance. The fields are
write-only — once saved, a field shows a **Set** badge and the input stays blank; leave it
blank on a later save to keep the existing value.

<Callout type="warning" title="Restart after saving">
  The bot reads its configuration once at startup. After saving or removing credentials in
  the Admin UI, <strong>restart the Nocturne web service</strong> for the change to take
  effect.
</Callout>

### Option B: Environment variables

For declarative, infrastructure-as-code deployments, set the platform's variables in your
`.env` or container environment and restart. The exact variable names are listed on each
platform's page.

<Callout type="info" title="Admin UI wins">
  If a platform is configured through the Admin UI, those values are used and the matching
  environment variables for that platform are ignored. Manage each platform in one place,
  not both.
</Callout>

<Callout type="tip" title="Encryption key">
  Saving credentials in the Admin UI requires the instance encryption key
  (<code>INSTANCE_KEY</code>) to be configured. It already is on any standard deployment.
</Callout>

## Webhooks

Each platform delivers messages to Nocturne by calling a webhook endpoint. You register these
URLs in the platform's developer console (the per-platform pages say exactly where). Replace
`your-instance.com` with your Nocturne domain:

| Platform | Webhook endpoint |
|----------|------------------|
| Discord | `https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/discord` |
| Slack | `https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/slack` |
| Telegram | `https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/telegram` |
| WhatsApp | `https://your-instance.com/api/v4/webhooks/whatsapp` |

## Receiving alerts

To push alerts to a connected platform:

1. Go to **Settings > Alerts**.
2. Create or edit an alert rule.
3. Under **Delivery channels**, add the platform.
4. Save the rule.

The recipient must have a linked account on that platform. When the rule fires, the alert is
delivered to their chat with inline **Acknowledge** and **Resolve** actions.

